Create a wallet - 1 Request in the folder
Iteration: 1 - 1. Create/Restore existing wallet
Request Description
A wallet is registered or retrieved by sending a request to all miners on the network. **Requirements to make this request:** **[BIP39](https://en.bitcoinwiki.org/wiki/Mnemonic_phrase) Mnemonic**: A 24 word representation of the wallet private key seed with a passphrase of "0chain-client-split-key". There are [utilities](https://iancoleman.io/bip39/) that can help you generate this. **BLS BN254 private key:** Thee private key generated from the BIP39 mnemonic seed. 0Chain Keys are [BLS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BLS_digital_signature) with a [BN254 curve](https://neuromancer.sk/std/bn/bn254) . There are [many](https://github.com/herumi/bls) / [libraries](https://github.com/herumi/bls-wasm) to help you generate this key. **BLS BN254 public key hex string**: The public key calculated from the previously generated private key, formatted as a hex string. **Client/wallet id**: A SHA3-256 hash of the public key **hex dump** - for an example of how this hex dump can be generated, see the pre-request script of this request in postman. A consensus of 20% is required from the miners, after which you can be sure that your request will be propagated. The example below shows a single miner call but assumes the call will be made to all miners retrieved in step 1

Iteration: 1 - Process and erasure code file
Request Description
After retrieving an allocation, the file should be processed for upload. Firstly, we need to record some file metadata: - the SHA1 hash of the file - the file size in bytes We also need to Reed-Solomon erasure code the file into multiple shards. Each shard will be uploaded to a different blobber in the allocation. None of the above is natively supported in postman so is accomplished by calling an external API that will return the file size, SHA1 hash and reed-solomon EC shards. The above data is trivial to calculate with a range of well supported libraries in most programming languages. Please do not attempt to upload files > 10M in size as this is a limitation of postman. A text file is recommended so you can easily visualise the EC shards

Iteration: 1 - 4. Commit Upoad of EC shard 1
Request Description
In a similar fashion to some databases, a file is not persisted permanently to the blobber until it is comitted. 0Chain keeps it's network fast by storing data off-chain while maintaining the benefits of on-chain storage by comitting the allocation metadata to the blockchain. A commit requires a write marker. Think of this as the latest entry in an audit trail containing the hash of the entire allocation at the time of upload and a link to the previous write market in the form of the hash of the previous allocation state. **This is a major benefit of 0chain - a GDPR compliant, transparent and immutable audit log is a mandatory feature of the platform.** **Requirements to make this request:** Create a new write marker using the reference path: - Set previous allocation root to current allocation root - Traverse through file tree until file path is reached - Add file metadata entry to that directory - recalculate directory hash - recalculate all parent directory hashes - recalculate root directory hash - set allocation root to root directory hash with timestamp - BLS signature sign the request Shard is now successfully uploaded to a blobber. **Now Repeat steps 3, 4 and 5 for each remaining blobber, postman will auto-increment the current blobber and EC shard for you**

Iteration: 1 - 7. Commit Upoad of EC shard 2
Request Description
In a similar fashion to some databases, a file is not persisted permanently to the blobber until it is comitted. 0Chain keeps it's network fast by storing data off-chain while maintaining the benefits of on-chain storage by comitting the allocation metadata to the blockchain. A commit requires a write marker. Think of this as the latest entry in an audit trail containing the hash of the entire allocation at the time of upload and a link to the previous write market in the form of the hash of the previous allocation state. **This is a major benefit of 0chain - a GDPR compliant, transparent and immutable audit log is a mandatory feature of the platform.** **Requirements to make this request:** Create a new write marker using the reference path: - Set previous allocation root to current allocation root - Traverse through file tree until file path is reached - Add file metadata entry to that directory - recalculate directory hash - recalculate all parent directory hashes - recalculate root directory hash - set allocation root to root directory hash with timestamp - BLS signature sign the request Shard is now successfully uploaded to a blobber. **Now Repeat steps 3, 4 and 5 for each remaining blobber, postman will auto-increment the current blobber and EC shard for you**

Iteration: 1 - 3. Get latest read marker on blobber for wallet's read pool
Request Description
The Read marker is another important feature of the network. It ensures that every download is recorded, tallied and transparent. Each blobber writes a read marker to the client's read pool when a file has been served. This ensures that blobbers are paid while keeping an audit. The read marker contains a counter of how many blocks have been read from the current blobber by the current pool, as well as the allocation id the read was requested from. All Allocations use the same read pool. At the point of download, a new read marker is written with an incremented counter
